    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. can you go a bit deeper into the mechanism though? like what's actually happening at the site of the infection that causes the bone marrow to push out more neutrophils specifically during a bacterial attack?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "During a bacterial invasion, the site of infection releases chemical signals called cytokines, like interleukins. These cytokines act as alarm bells, prompting the bone marrow to rapidly increase the production and release of neutrophils into the bloodstream. Neutrophils are the first responders, migrating quickly to phagocytize and destroy the invading bacteria. This rapid mobilization and proliferation of neutrophils is what drives neutrophilia in acute bacterial sepsis or abscess formation.",
      "source": "target",
