    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "got it. so if the neutrophils are the \"first responders\" and they're rushing to the site to fight, how does that compare to how the lymphocytes handle a chronic infection? is it a different kind of mobilization or something?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Lymphocytes handle a chronic infection through a more nuanced, adaptive response. Instead of a rapid, large-scale mobilization like neutrophils, lymphocytes are involved in a slower, highly specific immune surveillance. They are activated by antigen-presenting cells to become memory cells, allowing the body to develop long-term immunity against the persistent pathogen. This slower, targeted activation is the difference between the immediate \"firefighting\" of neutrophils and the organized, long-term \"strategy\" of lymphocytes.",
      "source": "target",
